b'<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>\n\n\n<!DOCTYPE workbook_page PUBLIC " -//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Workbook Page MathML 3.8//EN" "http://oli.web.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_workbook_page_mathml_3_8.dtd">\n<workbook_page id="p7a_balance_redox" xmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/"\n    xmlns:bib="http://bibtexml.sf.net/" xmlns:pref="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/preferences/"\n    xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:theme="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/presentation/"\n    xmlns:wb="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/activity/workbook/">\n\n\n    <head>\n        <title>Balancing Redox Equations in Acidic Solutions</title>\n        <objref idref="balance_redox"/>\n\n    </head>\n\n    <body>\n\n        <p>In this section, we will concentrate on the half-reaction method for balancing\n            oxidation-reduction reactions. The use of half-reactions is important for balancing more\n            complicated reactions and partly because many aspects of electrochemistry, which will be\n            discussed later in the course, are easier to discuss in terms of half-reactions. The\n            half-reaction method splits oxidation-reduction reactions into their oxidation \xe2\x80\x9chalf\xe2\x80\x9d\n            and reduction \xe2\x80\x9chalf\xe2\x80\x9d to make finding the overall equation easier.</p>\n        <p>Electrochemical reactions frequently occur in solutions, which could be acidic, basic, or\n            neutral. When balancing oxidation-reduction reactions, the nature of the solution may be\n            important. On this page, we will look at how to balance an oxidation-reduction reaction\n            in acidic solution.</p>\n        <image src="../../../webcontent/green_line.png"></image>\n        <dl>\n            <dt>Steps for Balancing Oxidation-Reduction Reactions in Acidic Solution</dt>\n            <dd>\n                <ul>\n                    <li>Write unbalanced half-reactions.</li>\n                    <li>Balance each half reaction: <ul>\n                            <li>First balance the elements (except for H and O).</li>\n                            <li>Balance O then H with H<sub>2</sub>O and H<sup>+</sup>\n                                respectively.</li>\n                            <li>Then balance charge by adding electrons.</li>\n                        </ul>\n                    </li>\n                    <li>Make the electrons gained and lost equal by multiplying the half-reactions\n                        by the appropriate factor.</li>\n                    <li>Add the balanced half-reactions together.</li>\n                    <li>Check the overall reaction to make sure the mass and charge are\n                        balanced.</li>\n                </ul>\n            </dd>\n        </dl>\n\n        <image src="../../../webcontent/green_line.png"></image>\n        <!--<image src="../../../webcontent/line.png" width="700"/>\n-->\n        <p> Consider the following unbalanced oxidation-reduction reaction in <em>acidic solution</em>:</p>\n        <formula>$${\\mathrm{MnO}}_4^-(aq)\\;+\\;\\mathrm{Fe}^{2+}(aq)\\;\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\;\\mathrm{Mn}^{2+}(aq)\\;+\\;\\mathrm{Fe}^{3+}(aq)$$</formula>\n\n        <ul>\n            <li><em>Write unbalanced half-reactions.</em></li>\n        </ul>\n        <p> Each half-reaction contains the same element in two different oxidation states. The\n                Fe<sup>2+</sup> has lost an electron to become Fe<sup>3+</sup>; therefore, the iron\n            underwent oxidation. The reduction is not as obvious; however, the manganese gained five\n            electrons to change from Mn<sup>7+</sup> (in MnO<sub>4</sub><sup>-</sup>) to\n                Mn<sup>2+</sup>.</p>\n        <formula>$$\\begin{array}{l}\\mathrm{oxidation}\\;(\\mathrm{unbalanced})\\;:\\;\\mathrm{Fe}^{2+}(aq)\\;\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\;\\mathrm{Fe}^{3+}(aq)\\\\\\mathrm{reduction}\\;(\\mathrm{unbalanced})\\;:\\;{\\mathrm{MnO}}_4^-(aq)\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\mathrm{Mn}^{2+}(aq)\\end{array}$$</formula>\n        <ul>\n            <li><em>Balance each half reaction:</em>\n                <ul>\n                    <li>First balance the elements (except for H and O).</li>\n                    <li>Balance O then H with H<sub>2</sub>O and H<sup>+</sup> respectively.</li>\n\n                    <li>Then balance charge by adding electrons.</li>\n                </ul>\n            </li>\n\n        </ul>\n        <p>The iron atoms in the oxidation half-reaction are balanced (mass balance); however, the\n            charge is unbalanced, since the charges on the ions are not equal. Adding a single\n            electron on the right side gives a balanced oxidation half-reaction:</p>\n        <formula>$$\\mathrm{oxidation}\\;(\\mathrm{balanced}):\\;\\mathrm{Fe}^{2+}(aq)\\;\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\;\\mathrm{Fe}^{3+}(aq)\\;+\\;\\mathrm\n            e^-$$</formula>\n        <p>The elements of the reduction half-reaction are not balanced. We must add 4 H2O to the\n            right side of the equation to balance the oxygen atoms and we then add 8 H+ ions to the\n            left side of the equation to balance the hydrogen.</p>\n\n        <formula>$$\\mathrm{charge}\\;\\mathrm{not}\\;\\mathrm{balanced}:\\;{\\mathrm{MnO}}_4^-(aq)\\;+\\;8\\;\\mathrm\n            H^+(aq)\\;\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\;\\mathrm{Mn}^{2+}(aq)\\;+\\;4\\;{\\mathrm H}_2\\mathrm\n            O(l)$$</formula>\n        <p>The atoms are balanced (mass balance), so it is now necessary to check for charge\n            balance. The total charge on the left of the reaction arrow is [(\xe2\x88\x921) \xc3\x97 (1) + (8) \xc3\x97\n            (+1)], or +7, while the total charge on the right side is [(1) \xc3\x97 (+2) + (4) \xc3\x97 (0)], or\n            +2. The difference between +7 and +2 is five; therefore, it is necessary to add five\n            electrons to the left side to achieve charge balance.</p>\n        <formula>$$\\mathrm{Reduction}\\;(\\mathrm{balanced}):\\;\\;{\\mathrm{MnO}}_4^-(aq)\\;+\\;8\\;\\mathrm\n            H^+(aq)\\;+\\;5\\;\\mathrm e^-\\;\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\;\\mathrm{Mn}^{2+}(aq)\\;+\\;4\\;{\\mathrm\n            H}_2\\mathrm O(l)$$</formula>\n        <p>We now have two balanced half-reactions.</p>\n        <formula>$$\\begin{array}{l}\\mathrm{oxidation}:\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm{Fe}^{2+}(aq)\\;\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\;\\mathrm{Fe}^{3+}(aq)\\;+\\;\\mathrm\n            e^-\\\\\\mathrm{reduction}:\\;\\;{\\mathrm{MnO}}_4^-(aq)\\;+\\;8\\;\\mathrm H^+(aq)\\;+\\;5\\;\\mathrm\n            e^-\\;\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\;\\mathrm{Mn}^{2+}(aq)\\;+\\;4\\;{\\mathrm H}_2\\mathrm\n            O(l)\\end{array}$$</formula>\n        <ul>\n            <li><em>Make the electrons gained and lost equal by multiplying the half-reactions by\n                    the appropriate factor.</em></li>\n        </ul>\n        <p>The number of electrons transferred from the oxidation half-reaction to the reduction\n            half-reaction must be equal. In this example, it is necessary to multiply every term in\n            the oxidation half-reaction by five. The multiplication of the two half-reactions by the\n            appropriate factor followed by addition of the two halves gives</p>\n        <formula>$$\\begin{array}{l}\\mathrm{oxidation}:\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;5\\;\\mathrm{Fe}^{2+}(aq)\\;\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\;5\\;\\mathrm{Fe}^{3+}(aq)\\;+\\;5\\;\\mathrm\n            e^-\\\\\\mathrm{reduction}:\\;\\;{\\mathrm{MnO}}_4^-(aq)\\;+\\;8\\;\\mathrm H^+(aq)\\;+\\;5\\;\\mathrm\n            e^-\\;\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\;\\mathrm{Mn}^{2+}(aq)\\;+\\;4\\;{\\mathrm H}_2\\mathrm\n            O(l)\\end{array}$$</formula>\n        <ul>\n            <li><em>Add the balanced half-reactions together.</em></li>\n        </ul>\n        <formula>$$\\begin{array}{l}\\mathrm{oxidation}:\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;5\\;\\mathrm{Fe}^{2+}(aq)\\;\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\;5\\;\\mathrm{Fe}^{3+}(aq)\\;+\\;5\\;\\mathrm\n            e^-\\\\\\underline{\\mathrm{reduction}:\\;\\;{\\mathrm{MnO}}_4^-(\\mathrm{aq})\\;+\\;8\\;\\mathrm\n            H^+(\\mathrm{aq})\\;+\\;5\\;\\mathrm\n            e^-\\;\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\;\\mathrm{Mn}^{2+}(\\mathrm{aq})\\;+\\;4\\;{\\mathrm H}_2\\mathrm\n            O(\\mathrm\n            l)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;}\\\\\\mathrm{overall}:\\;5\\;\\mathrm{Fe}^{2+}(aq)\\;+\\;{\\mathrm{MnO}}_4^-(aq)\\;+\\;8\\;\\mathrm\n            H^+(aq)\\;\\longrightarrow\\;5\\;\\mathrm{Fe}^{3+}(aq)\\;+\\;\\mathrm{Mn}^{2+}(aq)\\;+\\;4\\;{\\mathrm\n            H}_2\\mathrm O(l)\\end{array}$$</formula>\n        <p>The electrons do not appear in the final answer because the oxidation electrons are the\n            same electrons as the reduction electrons and they \xe2\x80\x9ccancel.\xe2\x80\x9d</p>\n        <ul>\n            <li><em>Check the overall reaction to make sure the mass and charge are\n                balanced</em>.</li>\n        </ul>\n        <formula>$$5\\;\\mathrm{Fe}^{2+}(aq)\\;+\\;{\\mathrm{MnO}}_4^-(aq)\\;+\\;8\\;\\mathrm\n            H^+(aq)\\;\\longrightarrow\\;5\\;\\mathrm{Fe}^{3+}(aq)\\;+\\;\\mathrm{Mn}^{2+}(aq)\\;+\\;4\\;{\\mathrm\n            H}_2\\mathrm O(l)$$</formula>\n        <formula>$$\\begin{array}{l}\\mathrm{Fe}:\\;(5\\times1)=(5\\times1)\\;-\\;\\mathrm{balanced}\\\\\\mathrm{Mn}:\\;(1\\times1)=(1\\times1)\\;-\\;\\mathrm{balanced}\\\\\\mathrm\n            H:\\;(8\\times1)=(4\\times2)\\;-\\;\\mathrm{balanced}\\\\\\mathrm\n            O:\\;(1\\times4)=(4\\times1)\\;-\\;\\mathrm{balanced}\\\\\\mathrm{Charge}:\\;\\lbrack5\\times(+2)+1\\times(-1)+8\\times(+1)\\rbrack\\;=\\;\\lbrack5\\times(+3)+1\\times(+2)\\rbrack\\;-\\;\\mathrm{balanced}\\end{array}$$</formula>\n        <example>\n            <title>Balancing Acidic Oxidation-Reduction Reactions</title>\n            <p>Balance the following reaction equation in acidic solution:</p>\n            <formula>$${\\mathrm{MnO}}_4^-(aq)\\;+\\;\\mathrm{Cr}^{3+}(aq)\\;\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\;\\mathrm{Mn}^{2+}(aq)\\;+\\;{\\mathrm{Cr}}_2{\\mathrm\n                O}_7^{2-}(aq)$$</formula>\n            <ul>\n                <li><em>Write unbalanced half-reactions.</em></li>\n            </ul>\n            <formula>$$\\begin{array}{l}\\mathrm{oxidation}\\;(\\mathrm{unbalanced}):\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm{Cr}^{3+}(aq)\\;\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\;{\\mathrm{Cr}}_2{\\mathrm\n                O}_7^{2-}(aq)\\\\\\mathrm{reduction}\\;(\\mathrm{unbalanced}):\\;\\;{\\mathrm{MnO}}_4^-(aq)\\;\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\;\\mathrm{Mn}^{2+}(aq)\\end{array}$$</formula>\n            <ul>\n                <li><em>Balance each half reaction: oxidation</em>\n                    <ul>\n                        <li>First balance the elements (except for H and O).\n                                <formula>$$\\require{color}\\mathrm{oxidation}\\;(\\mathrm{unbalanced}):\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;{\\color[rgb]{1.0,\n                                0.0,\n                                0.0}\\mathbf2}\\;\\mathrm{Cr}^{3+}(aq)\\;\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\;{\\mathrm{Cr}}_2{\\mathrm\n                                O}_7^{2-}(aq)$$</formula>\n                        </li>\n                        <li>Balance O then H with H<sub>2</sub>O and H<sup>+</sup> respectively.\n                                <p>In acidic solution, we can use or generate hydrogen ions (H+).\n                                Adding seven water molecules to the left side provides the necessary\n                                oxygen; the \xe2\x80\x9cleft over\xe2\x80\x9d hydrogen appears as 14 H+ on the right:</p>\n                            <formula>$$\\require{color}\\mathrm{oxidation}\\;(\\mathrm{unbalanced}):\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;{\\color[rgb]{0.1,\n                                0.1, 0.1}\\mathbf2}{\\color[rgb]{0.1, 0.1,\n                                0.1}\\;}\\mathrm{Cr}^{3+}(aq)\\;\\;+\\;{\\color[rgb]{1.0, 0.0,\n                                0.0}\\mathbf7}{\\color[rgb]{1.0, 0.0, 0.0}\\mathbf\\;}{\\color[rgb]{1.0,\n                                0.0, 0.0}{\\color[rgb]{1.0, 0.0, 0.0}\\mathbf\n                                H}_{\\mathbf2}}{\\color[rgb]{1.0, 0.0, 0.0}\\mathbf O}{\\color[rgb]{1.0,\n                                0.0, 0.0}\\mathbf\\;}{\\color[rgb]{1.0, 0.0,\n                                0.0}\\mathbf(}{\\color[rgb]{1.0, 0.0, 0.0}\\boldsymbol\n                                l}{\\color[rgb]{1.0, 0.0,\n                                0.0}\\mathbf)}\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\;{\\mathrm{Cr}}_2{\\mathrm\n                                O}_7^{2-}(aq)\\;+\\;{\\color[rgb]{1.0, 0.0,\n                                0.0}\\mathbf14}{\\color[rgb]{1.0, 0.0, 0.0}\\mathbf\\;}{\\color[rgb]{1.0,\n                                0.0, 0.0}{\\color[rgb]{1.0, 0.0, 0.0}\\mathbf\n                                H}^\\boldsymbol+}{\\color[rgb]{1.0, 0.0,\n                                0.0}\\mathbf(}{\\color[rgb]{1.0, 0.0, 0.0}\\boldsymbol\n                                a}{\\color[rgb]{1.0, 0.0, 0.0}\\boldsymbol q}{\\color[rgb]{1.0, 0.0,\n                                0.0}\\mathbf)}$$</formula>\n                        </li>\n                        <li> Balance charge by adding electrons. <p>The left side of the equation\n                                has a total charge of [2 \xc3\x97 (+3) = +6], and the right side a total\n                                charge of [\xe2\x88\x922 + 14 \xc3\x97 (+1) = +12]. The difference is six; adding six\n                                electrons to the right side produces a mass- and charge-balanced\n                                oxidation half-reaction (in acidic solution):</p>\n                            <formula>$$\\require{color}\\mathrm{oxidation}\\;(\\mathrm{unbalanced}):\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;{\\color[rgb]{0.1,\n                                0.1, 0.1}\\mathbf2}{\\color[rgb]{0.1, 0.1,\n                                0.1}\\;}\\mathrm{Cr}^{3+}(aq)\\;\\;+\\;{\\color[rgb]{0.1, 0.1,\n                                0.1}\\mathbf7}{\\color[rgb]{0.1, 0.1, 0.1}\\mathbf\\;}{\\color[rgb]{0.1,\n                                0.1, 0.1}{\\color[rgb]{0.1, 0.1, 0.1}\\mathbf\n                                H}_{\\mathbf2}}{\\color[rgb]{0.1, 0.1, 0.1}\\mathbf O}{\\color[rgb]{0.1,\n                                0.1, 0.1}\\mathbf\\;}{\\color[rgb]{0.1, 0.1,\n                                0.1}\\mathbf(}{\\color[rgb]{0.1, 0.1, 0.1}\\boldsymbol\n                                l}{\\color[rgb]{0.1, 0.1,\n                                0.1}\\mathbf)}\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\;{\\mathrm{Cr}}_2{\\mathrm\n                                O}_7^{2-}(aq)\\;+\\;{\\color[rgb]{0.1, 0.1,\n                                0.1}\\mathbf14}{\\color[rgb]{0.1, 0.1, 0.1}\\mathbf\\;}{\\color[rgb]{0.1,\n                                0.1, 0.1}{\\color[rgb]{0.1, 0.1, 0.1}\\mathbf\n                                H}^\\boldsymbol+}{\\color[rgb]{0.1, 0.1,\n                                0.1}\\mathbf(}{\\color[rgb]{0.1, 0.1, 0.1}\\boldsymbol\n                                a}{\\color[rgb]{0.1, 0.1, 0.1}\\boldsymbol q}{\\color[rgb]{0.1, 0.1,\n                                0.1}\\mathbf)}{\\color[rgb]{0.1, 0.1, 0.1}\\mathbf\\;}{\\color[rgb]{0.1,\n                                0.1, 0.1}\\mathbf+}{\\color[rgb]{0.1, 0.1,\n                                0.1}\\mathbf\\;}{\\color[rgb]{1.0, 0.0, 0.0}\\mathbf6}{\\color[rgb]{1.0,\n                                0.0, 0.0}\\mathbf\\;}{\\color[rgb]{1.0, 0.0, 0.0}{\\color[rgb]{1.0, 0.0,\n                                0.0}\\mathbf e}^\\boldsymbol-}$$</formula>\n                        </li>\n\n                    </ul>\n                </li>\n            </ul>\n            <ul>\n                <li><em>Balance each half reaction: reduction</em>\n                    <ul>\n                        <li>Balance O then H with H<sub>2</sub>O and H<sup>+</sup> respectively.\n                                <p>It is necessary to convert the four oxygen atoms in the\n                                permanganate into four water molecules. To do this, add eight H+ to\n                                convert the oxygen into four water molecules:</p>\n                            <formula>$$\\require{color}\\mathrm{reduction}\\;(\\mathrm{unbalanced}):\\;\\;{\\mathrm{MnO}}_4^-(aq)\\;+{\\color[rgb]{1.0,\n                                0.0, 0.0}\\mathbf\\;}{\\color[rgb]{1.0, 0.0,\n                                0.0}\\mathbf8}{\\color[rgb]{1.0, 0.0, 0.0}\\mathbf\\;}{\\color[rgb]{1.0,\n                                0.0, 0.0}{\\color[rgb]{1.0, 0.0, 0.0}\\mathbf\n                                H}^\\boldsymbol+}{\\color[rgb]{1.0, 0.0,\n                                0.0}\\mathbf(}{\\color[rgb]{1.0, 0.0, 0.0}\\boldsymbol\n                                a}{\\color[rgb]{1.0, 0.0, 0.0}\\boldsymbol q}{\\color[rgb]{1.0, 0.0,\n                                0.0}\\mathbf)}\\;\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\;\\mathrm{Mn}^{2+}(aq)\\;+{\\color[rgb]{1.0,\n                                0.0, 0.0}\\mathbf\\;}{\\color[rgb]{1.0, 0.0,\n                                0.0}\\mathbf4}{\\color[rgb]{1.0, 0.0, 0.0}\\mathbf\\;}{\\color[rgb]{1.0,\n                                0.0, 0.0}{\\color[rgb]{1.0, 0.0, 0.0}\\mathbf\n                                H}_{\\mathbf2}}{\\color[rgb]{1.0, 0.0, 0.0}\\mathbf O}{\\color[rgb]{1.0,\n                                0.0, 0.0}\\mathbf(}{\\color[rgb]{1.0, 0.0, 0.0}\\boldsymbol\n                                l}{\\color[rgb]{1.0, 0.0, 0.0}\\mathbf)}$$</formula>\n                        </li>\n                    </ul>\n                    <ul>\n                        <li>Balance charge by adding electrons. <p>Add five electrons to the left\n                                side to balance the charge.</p>\n                            <formula>$$\\require{color}\\mathrm{reduction}\\;(\\mathrm{unbalanced}):\\;\\;{\\mathrm{MnO}}_4^-(aq)\\;+{\\color[rgb]{1.0,\n                                0.0, 0.0}\\mathbf\\;}{\\color[rgb]{0.1, 0.1,\n                                0.1}\\mathbf8}{\\color[rgb]{0.1, 0.1, 0.1}\\mathbf\\;}{\\color[rgb]{0.1,\n                                0.1, 0.1}{\\color[rgb]{0.1, 0.1, 0.1}\\mathbf\n                                H}^\\boldsymbol+}{\\color[rgb]{0.1, 0.1,\n                                0.1}\\mathbf(}{\\color[rgb]{0.1, 0.1, 0.1}\\boldsymbol\n                                a}{\\color[rgb]{0.1, 0.1, 0.1}\\boldsymbol q}{\\color[rgb]{0.1, 0.1,\n                                0.1}\\mathbf)}{\\color[rgb]{0.1, 0.1, 0.1}\\;}\\;+\\;{\\color[rgb]{1.0,\n                                0.0, 0.0}\\mathbf5}{\\color[rgb]{1.0, 0.0,\n                                0.0}\\mathbf\\;}{\\color[rgb]{1.0, 0.0, 0.0}{\\color[rgb]{1.0, 0.0,\n                                0.0}\\mathbf\n                                e}^\\boldsymbol-}\\longrightarrow\\;\\;\\mathrm{Mn}^{2+}(aq)\\;+{\\color[rgb]{1.0,\n                                0.0, 0.0}\\mathbf\\;}{\\color[rgb]{0.1, 0.1,\n                                0.1}\\mathbf4}{\\color[rgb]{0.1, 0.1, 0.1}\\mathbf\\;}{\\color[rgb]{0.1,\n                                0.1, 0.1}{\\color[rgb]{0.1, 0.1, 0.1}\\mathbf\n                                H}_{\\mathbf2}}{\\color[rgb]{0.1, 0.1, 0.1}\\mathbf O}{\\color[rgb]{0.1,\n                                0.1, 0.1}\\mathbf(}{\\color[rgb]{0.1, 0.1, 0.1}\\boldsymbol\n                                l}{\\color[rgb]{0.1, 0.1, 0.1}\\mathbf)}$$</formula>\n                        </li>\n                    </ul>\n                </li>\n\n            </ul>\n\n            <ul>\n                <li><em>Make the electrons gained and lost equal by multiplying the half-reactions\n                        by the appropriate factor.</em></li>\n            </ul>\n            <ul>\n                <li><em>Add the balanced half-reactions together.</em></li>\n            </ul>\n            <p>The least common multiple for the electrons is 30, so multiply the oxidation\n                half-reaction by five, the reduction half-reaction by six.</p>\n            <formula>$$\\require{cancel}\\begin{array}{l}\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;10\\;\\mathrm{Cr}^{3+}(aq)\\;+\\;35\\;{\\mathrm\n                H}_2\\mathrm O(l)\\;\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\;5\\;{\\mathrm{Cr}}_2{\\mathrm\n                O}_7^{2-}(aq)\\;+\\;70\\;\\mathrm H^+(aq)\\;+\\;\\cancel{30\\;\\mathrm\n                e^-}\\;\\;\\\\\\underline{6\\;{\\mathrm{MnO}}_4^-(aq)\\;+\\;48\\;\\mathrm\n                H^+(aq)\\;+\\;\\cancel{30\\;\\mathrm\n                e^-}\\;\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\;6\\;\\mathrm{Mn}^{2+}(aq)\\;\\;+\\;24\\;{\\mathrm H}_2\\mathrm\n                O(l)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;}\\\\6\\;{\\mathrm{MnO}}_4^-(aq)\\;+\\;10\\;\\mathrm{Cr}^{3+}(aq)\\;+\\;11\\;{\\mathrm\n                H}_2\\mathrm O(l)\\;\\;\\rightarrow\\;\\;5\\;{\\mathrm{Cr}}_2{\\mathrm\n                O}_7^{2-}(aq)\\;+\\;6\\;\\mathrm{Mn}^{2+}(aq)\\;+\\;22\\;\\mathrm\n                H^+(aq)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\\\\\end{array}$$</formula>\n            <ul>\n                <li><em>Check the overall reaction to make sure the mass and charge are\n                        balanced.</em></li>\n            </ul>\n            <formula>$$\\begin{array}{l}\\mathrm{Mn}:\\;(6\\times1)\\;=\\;(6\\times1)\\;-\\;\\mathrm{balanced}\\\\\\mathrm{Cr}:\\;(10\\times1)\\;=\\;(5\\times2)\\;-\\;\\mathrm{balanced}\\\\\\mathrm\n                H:\\;(11\\times2)\\;=\\;(22\\times1)\\;-\\;\\mathrm{balanced}\\\\\\mathrm\n                O:\\;(11\\times1+6\\times4)\\;=\\;(5\\times7)\\;-\\;\\mathrm{balanced}\\\\\\mathrm{Charge}:\\;\\lbrack10\\times(+3)+6\\times(-1)\\rbrack\\;=\\;\\lbrack5\\times(-2)+22\\times(+1)+6\\times(+2)\\rbrack\\;-\\;\\mathrm{balanced}\\end{array}$$</formula>\n\n        </example>\n\n        <composite_activity purpose="learnbydoing">\n            <p>Follow the steps below to balance the following reaction in acidic solution. </p>\n            <formula>$${\\mathrm\n                H}_2\\;+\\;\\mathrm{Cu}^{2+}\\;\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\;\\mathrm{Cu}$$</formula>\n\n            <wb:inline idref="balance_acidic_lbd" purpose="learnbydoing"/>\n        </composite_activity>\n        <composite_activity purpose="learnbydoing">\n            <p>Follow the steps below to balance the following reaction in acidic solution. </p>\n            <formula>$${\\mathrm P}_2{\\mathrm\n                O}_3(s)\\;+\\;{\\mathrm{NO}}_3^-(aq)\\;\\;\\rightarrow\\;\\;{\\mathrm\n                H}_3{\\mathrm{PO}}_4(aq)\\;+\\;\\mathrm{NO}(g)$$</formula>\n            <wb:inline idref="balance_acidic_2lbd"/>\n\n        </composite_activity>\n        <composite_activity purpose="didigetthis">\n            <formula>$${\\mathrm H}_2{\\mathrm\n                O}_2\\;+\\;\\mathrm{Sn}^{2+}\\;\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\;{\\mathrm H}_2\\mathrm\n                O\\;+\\;\\mathrm{Sn}^{4+}$$</formula>\n            <wb:inline idref="balance_acidic_digt" purpose="didigetthis"/>\n        </composite_activity>\n        <composite_activity purpose="didigetthis">\n            <formula>$$\\mathrm{Al}\\;+\\;{\\mathrm{Cr}}_2{\\mathrm\n                O}_7^{2-}\\;\\;\\rightarrow\\;\\;\\mathrm{Al}^{3+}\\;+\\;\\mathrm{Cr}^{3+}$$</formula>\n            <wb:inline idref="balance_acidic2_digt"/>\n        </composite_activity>\n\n        <p>Adapted from <link href="https://cnx.org/contents/havxkyvS@9.422:b39avmGq@29/Preface"\n                >Openstax Chemistry</link> under <link\n                href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/"> Creative Commons Attribution\n                4.0 License. </link></p>\n        <p>Download for free at <link\n                href="http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312"\n                >http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312.</link></p>\n\n\n    </body>\n</workbook_page>\n'